When I was a child, my parents divorced when I was very young. My mom moved back to the town where her parents lived, and because she worked long hours, I spent most of my childhood with my grandparents. I really do miss them. My fondest memories are with my grandfather.

He worked in construction when he first came to the United States. He started at the bottom, worked his way up to foreman, and eventually went back to school to become an engineer. My grandparents bought a piece of property on a lake in the 1930s or 1940s. I’ve seen old photos of them from the 1920s and 30s—when they first met on the ship coming to America. They married soon after arriving, worked incredibly hard, and eventually that lake property became their retirement cabin. My grandfather built the cabin himself, using all the skills he had learned.

I spent so much time there growing up. I remember sitting on my grandmother’s lap while she knitted, talking to her about my day while she listened quietly and nodded. I followed my grandfather everywhere. He always had his big tool belt on, and my grandmother always had a list of little projects for him. I’d watch him work, hand him tools, and admire how skilled he was. I think that’s a big part of why I became an engineer—I wanted to follow in his footsteps and build things the way he did.

As for my adult life, I spent many years in a long relationship with my ex. But we didn’t communicate well. She worked two jobs, spent a lot of money, and we barely saw each other. Over time, the distance between us grew, and without talking or spending time together, frustration built up. It took years for us to reach a place where we could communicate again—mostly because we needed to co‑parent our daughter. We’re not friends, but we’re no longer enemies, and that’s what matters for our child.

Now, what I want most is a relationship where I can talk openly with someone, be friends with them, and spend real time together. I don’t need anything fancy—just walking together, holding hands, sitting on a bench, enjoying each other’s company. I want someone I can talk to about anything, someone who listens, someone I can trust. I believe love is built on friendship, and friendship is built on communication and trust. Those things take time, but they’re the foundation of a good relationship.
